 (1883) -- t"An Examination of a Noble Sentiment" (c. 1887) -- tChapter 6. War -- t"Essays on War" (1916) -- tChapter 7. Democracy -- t"When Parliament Cannot be Sovereign" (1931) -- t"Political Leadership and Democracy" (1942) -- tChapter 8. The Limits of Rationalism -- t"Speech on Rebuilding the House of Commons" (1943) -- t"Rationalism in Politics" (1947) -- t"The Errors of Constructivism" (1970) and The Mirage of Social Justice (1973) -- tThe Unheavenly City Revisited (1974) -- tChapter 9. The Critique of Social and Cultural Emancipation -- t"Pornography, Obscenity, and the Case for Censorship" (1971) -- tTo Empower People: The Role of Mediating Structures in Public Policy (1977 -- t"The Social Consequences of Attempts to Create Equality" (1984) -- tChapter 10. Between Social Science and Cultural Criticism -- t"On Culture, Nature, and Naturalness" (1958) and "Man and Institutions" (1960) -- t"Toward a Theory of Culture" (1966) -- tAfterword: Recurrent Tensions and Dilemmas of Conservative Thought -- tGuide to Further Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt a time when the label "conservative" is indiscriminately applied to fundamentalists, populists, libertarians, fascists, and the advocates of one or another orthodoxy, this volume offers a nuanced and historically informed presentation of what is distinctive about conservative social and political thought. It is an anthology with an argument, locating the origins of modern conservatism within the Enlightenment and distinguishing between conservatism and orthodoxy. Bringing together important specimens of European and American conservative social and political analysis from the mid-eighteenth century through our own day, Conservatism demonstrates that while the particular institutions that conservatives have sought to conserve have varied, there are characteristic features of conservative argument that recur over time and across national borders. The book proceeds chronologically through the following sections: Enlightenment Conservatism (David Hume, Edmund Burke, and Justus Möser), The Critique of Revolution (Burke, Louis de Bonald, Joseph de Maistre, James Madison, and Rufus Choate), Authority (Matthew Arnold, James Fitzjames Stephen), Inequality (W. H. Mallock, Joseph A. Schumpeter), The Critique of Good Intentions (William Graham Sumner), War (T. E. Hulme), Democracy (Carl Schmitt, Schumpeter), The Limits of Rationalism (Winston Churchill, Michael Oakeshott, Friedrich Hayek, Edward Banfield), The Critique of Social and Cultural Emancipation (Irving Kristol, Peter Berger and Richard John Neuhaus, Hermann Lübbe), and Between Social Science and Cultural Criticism (Arnold Gehlen, Philip Rieff). The book contains an afterword on recurrent tensions and dilemmas of conservative thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAmerican Revolution.  aBerger, Peter L.  aBonald, Louis de.  aBurke, Edmund.  aChristianity.  aFrench Revolution.  aGehlen, Arnold.  aNational Socialism.  aOakeshott, Michael.  aSchmitt, Carl.  aSoviet Union.  aauthority.  acapitalism.  aconventions.  ademocracy.  aduty.  afamily.  agovernment.  ahabit.  ahistorical utilitarianism.  ainequality.  ajustice.  alaw.  aliberalism, liberals.  amiddle class.  amonarchy.  apopulism.  aproperty.  apublic opinion.  areason.  areligion.  asocial contract.  astate.  atradition.1 aArnold, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanfield, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Peter L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonald, Louis de, econtributor.4